DORIAN WHO is pleased to announce the launch of our new collection, “NOOR,” shining a light on the ongoing desire for change and empowerment through women's voices on February 1st. This collection is a continuation of the experiences of our Iranian/Canadian Creative Director and the emerging movements around the world. Introducing our NOOR collection 🕯️

The name NOOR comes from the word light in Farsi. As this collections aims to shine light on the rise of movements against oppression around the world.

By bending gender norms through using androgynous structures this collection hopes to emulate the boundaries broken in society to create equality.

First look: warrior in life- The blazer and Tie are from our upcycled line. Handwritten messages by myself , inspired by words and chants that I have seen and read throughout the process of my design. Including names that I wanted to keep alive.

Second look - Our first genderless Varsity jacket made from deadstock quilted velvet and jacquards, with dyed buttons.

Breaking: #Pirooz, Iran’s last and one of the world’s few surviving Asiatic Cheetahs, has died of acute kidney failure. Pirooz (translates to “victorious”) is lovingly known as the “sweet son of #Iran” and even mentioned in @shervinine’s song #Baraye. The beautiful, rare and endangered “mascot of the #IranRevolution” gained global attention and was seen by many Iranians as a “symbol of hope”. Born in captivity 10 months ago, the ongoing neglect and now death of this rare cheetah is an embodiment of the lack of regard the Islamic Republic has for all life. As said yesterday when he was in need of a dialysis machine, “Millions and millions worth of the wealth of this ancient land have been looted, and they do not care for the environment either.“ #IRGCterrorists kill our children, our women, our men, our animals and our environment. #JinJiyanAzadi #FreeIran #womanlifefreedom

Woman, Life and Freedom 🤍 Forever

"Women, Life, Freedom," refers to the importance of women not only in the inner structure of society and families but in positions of leadership in politics. Women in positions of power in the government create the link between freedom and progress for women’s liberation. The symbolic movement for taking off the headscarf, leaving the house without the obligatory headscarf, and cutting one's hair is a social performance that fights against the oppression that attacks women’s bodies, identities, and desires. What should be noted is that the transformation and enlightenment of Iranian society in the shadow of Iranian women's street campaigns in recent days has brought together many social and religious groups, igniting men's support for women's rights.

These women-led protests are an alarm for the Islamic government's ideological education that promises to send out the message of the revolution that has always exploited women, their bodies, and identities as tools in fighting against the West. For more than forty years, the Islamic government promoted an education that portrayed women as men’s property to protect from modernism and imperialism; however, above all, it was a means of controlling women and preventing their takeover of power in society. The Islamic government used religion as a tool to infiltrate the family structure and incite a war that enforced hijab rules and oppressed women as a means to defend Islam, thereby victimizing women in Islamic society.

On International Women’s Day, I stand with the women and girls in Iran and outside of iran who have been fighting this fight for a long time. The world has started to see what we have gone through! Free Iran! Free women!

@smythebrand is launching a limited-edition collection
in support of the Women Life Freedom Movement. 
Eleven SMYTHE pieces have been hand-painted
by graffiti artist Chiara Catalano,
featuring quotes selected to embolden the feminine spirit. The collection is on preview at SMYTHE Summerhill
for the month and will be released for auction at the event.
The online auction will be live from March 30th to April 2nd. SMYTHE will donate 100% of proceeds to Amnesty International’s work in Iran, dedicated to fighting for human rights. #womanlifefreedom

I’m incredibly honoured and excited to announce that I’m one of the 9 finalists for @theamiriprize @mikeamiri @amiri 

This is another huge milestone of recognition and I thank everyone that has believed, supported and helped me build this vision! This is a dream come come true! Thank you @theamiriprize @mikeamiri for this opportunity! I’m beyond excited!

I don’t regret what I’ve been through. I’ve had ups and downs, super highs and some really low lows. I’ve been so blessed that I could never say, I wish this didn’t happen. It’s part of WHO I am.
This happened last month when I had a panic attack and couldn’t move from a severe back pain! It was painful and scary! I was exhausted and hopeless but still hoping! 
I believe hope is a powerful thing. It inspires us to do the impossible and helps us carry on during difficult times. 
So, whatever you’re going through just try not to lose your hope! Because we all go through shit! All of us in our own way! Sending love to anyone who may need it today! You’re not alone! Woman life freedom🤍
